    "analysis": "Trace aggregation was computed for the incident window and returned: all 208 distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) trace series had anomaly_count>0 (208), but this is misleading because many trace error_rate series have global P95 == 0.0 so every zero value in-window meets value >= global_p95, producing false positives. Metric analysis already shows widespread DB-related KPI anomalies (many db_* services with 'Hang'==1, 'On_Off_State'==1, MEM_Total anomalies) with earliest anomalies at 2020-05-23 04:30:00 CST. To localize the root cause component we should focus on traces that measure latency/duration (not error_rate) because duration spikes will better indicate downstream faulty containers/services in call chains. Next, we must extract trace series whose names indicate duration/latency (e.g., 'duration', 'duration_mean', 'latency', 'remoteprocess.duration') and compute their global P95 using full trace.csv, then inspect the incident window for anomaly counts and severity (max value). This will help identify the most downstream faulty container/service and the exact occurrence time.",
