{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold metric scanning and trace duration filtering. Metric results strongly indicate many DB services (db_001, db_002, db_003, db_004, ...) have persistent anomalies across multiple KPIs (Hang==1, On_Off_State==1, MEM_Total anomalies, etc.) with earliest anomalous points at 2020-05-23 04:30:00 CST. Trace duration analysis shows notable latency spikes around 2020-05-23 04:50:00 CST on os_021 and docker_003/docker_004 (anomaly_count small, only a couple of points), which look like secondary latency effects rather than the primary widespread DB problem starting at 04:30. Since many db_* services show simultaneous full-window anomalies (anomaly_count == window_point_count) beginning at 04:30, this suggests a DB-level outage starting at 04:30. To pick the exact root cause component among db_* services and the precise occurrence time, we should quantify anomaly severity per db component (how many KPI-series are anomalous and how many anomalous points each has) and get the earliest anomaly timestamp per db component. That will reveal the predominant (most affected) DB component and the root cause occurrence time (the earliest anomaly among DB KPIs).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomaly results already stored in kernel memory (the table you previously produced), filter to cmdb_id that start with 'db_'. For each such cmdb_id compute: 1) num_kpi_series_scanned (count of distinct kpi_name scanned for that db), 2) num_kpi_with_anomaly (count of kpi series with anomaly_count>0), 3) total_anomalous_points (sum of anomaly_count across all its kpi series), 4) earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window among its kpi series with anomaly_count>0), and 5) top_kpis (up to 5 kpi_name values for that db sorted by anomaly_count desc; include anomaly_count for each). Return a compact table sorted by total_anomalous_points descending (limit to top 20 rows) and also return the total number of distinct db_* cmdb_id scanned. Only include the specified aggregate columns and the top_kpis string per row."
}

